This adds a new field `platform_abi` in our egg metadata, thus defining a new metadata version format `1.4`.

The main rationale is to differentiate between non python packages which may have different ABIs (think Qt built w/ different versions of Visual Studio, as will be required to support python 3). For existing eggs, we can guess it from other tags (platform and python version).

@sjagoe

Consider:

```python
class M(Model):

    f = StringType()

    @serializable
    def s(self):
        return 'foo'
```

Since `M.f == M._fields['f']`, I would expect `M.s == M._serializables['s']` to be true as well.

But accessing `M.s` currently results in `M.s()` to be evaluated as if it were a classmethod. I suspect this is not by design. Does anyone else see a reason why this should be so?

Added the configuration stanza for interface-set
Both transitive and non transitive instance of the community are supported

flow {
        route MYROUTE {
                match {
                        source 1.1.1.1/32;
                        destination 2.2.2.2/32;
                }
                scope {
                        interface-set [  transitive:input:3000:3 non-transitive:output:12:1 transitive:input-output:1:1   ];
                }
                then {
                        accept;
                }
        }
}


Signed-off-by: Stephane Litkowski <stephane.litkowski@orange.com>

So I can override the view like this:

```python
from oscarapi.views.basket import AddProductView as _AddProductView

class AddProductView(_AddProductView):
    def validate(self, basket, product, quantity):
        # check if there is a orderlimit for this product
        allowed, message = basket.add_product_allowed(product, quantity)
        if not allowed:
            return False, message
        return super(
            AddProductView, self).validate(basket, product, quantity)
```

This should fix #195. Increment should reflect the largest increment with respect to the previous line, which is not what the previous code was doing. If run in a for loop, for some reason it was accumulating the increments, which was explaining why some people were seeing large negative increments (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51077423/strange-negative-value-in-memory-profiler-while-reading-file-python)

I also disabled a test that was assuming that the increment of a function that deletes its temporaries need to be zero, which given the above was a wrong test.

